<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1175,2014]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,373,1253,1279]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Description of</emphasis>
<specimenCount box="[381,403,1253,1279]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Chao, H. - F." box="[420,581,1253,1279]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 56" refId="ref29353" refString="Chao, H. - F. (1953 b) The external morphology of the dragonfly Onychogomphus ardens Needham. Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections, 122 (6), 1 - 56, figs 1 - 50." type="journal article" year="1953">Chao (1953b)</bibRefCitation>
has provided an exhaustive description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Needham" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[1084,1201,1253,1278]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Melligomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ardens">
<emphasis box="[1084,1201,1253,1278]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">M. ardens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in the form of a monograph detailing its external morphology. An abbreviated description is provided here. Male. – Labium pale cream with pale brownish edges. Labrum black with a pair of large yellow spots (
<figureCitation box="[1167,1268,1330,1356]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18a</figureCitation>
). Anteclypeus yellow, postclypeus black. Antefrons black. Postfrons broadly black at base; distal half occupied by narrowly divided yellow transerse, crest stripe. Synthorax black with a yellow dorsal stripe connected to yellow collar stripe (
<figureCitation box="[232,374,1446,1472]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Figs. 18b–c</figureCitation>
), the latter narrowly divided at centre. Pair of additional, narrowly isolated, yellow stripes located adjacent and anterior to the collar on the spiracular dorsum (
<figureCitation box="[954,1055,1485,1511]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18c</figureCitation>
). Small isolated superior yellow spot. Mesepimeron with a broad yellow stripe. Metepisternum black with yellow stripe reduced to small isolated superior spot (below wing base) and small isolated central stripe (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1192,1562,1588]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig 18b</figureCitation>
). Metepimeron and metaposternum yellow. Legs black. Wings hyaline with amber-enfumed bases to triangle. Base of hindwing illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[314,412,1640,1666]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18i</figureCitation>
. Abdomen S1 black above, yellow below. S2 black above with a yellow triangularshaped spot just above the auricle; auricle yellow; ventero-lateral, basal black spot and L-shaped yellow spot at distal, venter-lateral margin. S3–6 black with a large yellow dorsal, triangular spot at base. Dorsum S8 with pair of prominent, rounded-tipped, conical humps, located at centre of segment (
<figureCitation box="[1093,1230,1756,1782]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Figs. 18e–f</figureCitation>
). S7 yellow basal half, black distally. S8–10 black and anal appendages black. Hamules illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[1182,1318,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1239,1284,1794,1820]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="g" value="18.0">18g</quantity>
–h
</figureCitation>
. Superior appendages slightly curved at tip but not hooked and reflexed into the inferior appendages as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1922" box="[151,346,1872,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Lamelligomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,346,1872,1897]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Lamelligomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Valules prominent, rounded and oblong, illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[996,1098,1872,1898]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,255,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[176,1408,197,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[176,1409,197,1908]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18(a–i): Melligomphus ardens, Guangdong, ♂. (a) head, frontal, (b) synthorax and basal abdomen, lateral, (c) synthorax, dorsal, (d) caudal abdomen, ventral, (e) caudal abdomen, dorsal, (f) caudal abdomen, lateral, (g) anterior hamulus, (h) posterior hamulus, (i) base of hindwing." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18d</figureCitation>
. Inferior appendages acutely angled at ventero-basal corner extending well beyond the length of the superior appendages. Penile organ is illutrated in 
<figureCitation box="[294,393,1949,1975]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="37.[151,259,1901,1925]" captionTargetBox="[190,1402,194,1874]" captionTargetId="figure-83@37.[190,1403,194,1878]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 19(a–f): Melligomphus. [a–c] Melligomphus ardens, Fujian, ♂, from Chao (1953) as Onychogomphus ardens— (a) forewing, (b) hindwing, (c) penile organ; (d) Onychogomphus sinicus, ♂, penile organ, from Chao (1990), (e) Melligomphus cataractus, ♂, penile organ, from Chao (1990), (g) Onychogomphus sinicus, ♂, hamuli, from Chao (1990), (f) Melligomphus ludens, ♂, penile organ, from Chao (1990)." pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 19c</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
